AB  - The frequency and intensity of climate-induced disasters, such as floods, are increasing globally, and Nepal is no exception. Floods have a profound negative impact on agricultural production, exacerbating food insecurity and poverty. Despite this, studies on farmers' flood adaptation strategies are limited, especially in developing countries like Nepal, creating a huge knowledge gap. This paper aims to address that gap by exploring the variables influencing farmers' decisions on flood adaptation strategies through a cross-sectional household survey conducted in the Mohana-Khutiya and East Rapti River Basins in the Chure-Terai Region (CTR) of Nepal. The results of the study show that 41 % of farmers relocated assets as a pre-flood adaption strategy. House insurance was used as a pre-flood strategy only in the East Rapti River Basin. As post-flood coping strategies, approximately 71 % of farm households used savings and 11 % sent their family members as temporary migrants. Additionally, households adopted seed and grain storage, cultivation techniques, and engineering and bioengineering measures. A Multivariate Probit analysis indicated that various variables, such as farmers' perception, socioeconomic characteristics (age, education, and household's proximity to road), farm characteristics (ownership, size, and livestock), and institutional conditions (access to irrigation, credit, and government relief programmes), had a significant impact on flood adaptation strategies. While the surveyed households demonstrated high levels of awareness of early warning systems, no correlation was observed between this awareness and flood adaptation strategies. Therefore, local governments need to consider these factors when developing policies and programmes for supporting farmers in adapting to flood risks.
