KW  - Climate change
AB  - The sustainability of cocoa farming is critical for the environmental health of Ghana. As the industry faces climate change challenges, adopting sustainable farming practices becomes imperative. Understanding how gender plays out in the context of sustainable cocoa farming is essential for developing targeted interventions that can effectively promote the adoption of eco-friendly practices among all cocoa farmers. Using a multistage sampling technique to select 401 farmers, we employed probit regression analyses. Both male and female cocoa farmers generally perceive the benefits of sustainable agricultural practices positively, with slight differences in their views. Gender differences exist in adoption of specific sustainable cocoa farming practices. For both genders, age and type of cocoa farming system positively influences adoption. Membership in cooperatives negatively affects adoption for both genders. Both genders rank lack of technical assistance and extension as the most critical barrier. Addressing these constraints through enhanced extension services, improved market infrastructure, and comprehensive educational programs is essential for promoting sustainable cocoa farming practices in Ghana.
