AB  - Herbicide use is crucial for weed control but raises environmental concerns. Drought, a climate-related disaster, can alter weed-crop interactions and herbicide efficacy. Despite its potential implications, the impact of drought on farmers' herbicide use is underexplored. Based on the 2266 observations of herbicide usage for each crop planted by Chinese rural households in 2022, the study constructs an econometric model to investigate the effect of agricultural drought intensity on herbicide use intensity. The results indicate that agricultural drought intensity has a significant positive effect on herbicide use intensity, with a one-point increase in agricultural drought intensity corresponding to a 143.85 ml(g)/ha increase in herbicide use intensity. The results are robust to statistical test. Notably, the effect is more pronounced for households with lower environmental awareness and less evident among those with higher income or larger farm size. To mitigate this effect, the study recommends promoting drought-resistant crops, improving herbicide application methods, and offering technical training to farmers.
