AB  - Purpose-This study aims to investigate the behavioral, socio-economic, and institutional factors influencing smallholder farmers' decisions to adopt organic rice farming in Vietnam, a developing country facing both climate change challenges and the need for sustainable agricultural transformation. Design/Methodology/Approach-An integrated conceptual framework was developed by combining the Theory of Planned Behavior (TPB), the Technology Acceptance Model (TAM), and the Diffusion of Innovation (DOI) theory. A cross-sectional survey was conducted with 316 rice-farming households in the Mekong River Delta. Binary logistic regression, structural equation modeling, and response surface plot analysis were employed to examine the effects of cognitive, social, technical, and institutional variables, including moderating effects of government support and organic certification accessibility. Findings-The results reveal that perceived economic benefit, attitude toward organic farming, and access to extension services are the strongest predictors of adoption. Institutional factors, such as government support policies and the availability of organic certification, were found to significantly moderate the relationships between behavioral predictors and adoption decisions. Additionally, the nonlinear interaction between perceived benefits and attitude highlights a synergistic effect that substantially increases the adoption probability when both variables are high. Implications and Recommendations-The findings suggest the need for integrated policy interventions that combine economic incentives, technical training, trust-building measures, and accessible certification systems. A multi-actor approach involving government agencies, farmers, and civil society is recommended to scale up organic agriculture.
