KW  - Sub-Saharan Africa
KW  - CONSANGUINEOUS MARRIAGE
KW  - TRANSITIONS
KW  - CATTLE
AB  - Climate change presents an existential threat to rural, agrarian people in Sub-Saharan Africa, affecting not just quantifiable measures such as crop yield and livestock holdings, but embedded social practices as well. Changes in these social practices could lead to reduced climate resilience and demographic change. This review examines the literature on one social practice, the paying of bride price, usually in cattle, and asks how climate change may be affecting the custom, thus changing socio-demographic outcomes. Based on a review of the literature, I develop four models of how climate change may be driving changes in bride price practices and what the knock-on effects might be for current and future socio-demographic outcomes. Outcomes considered include lower ages at marriage for women/girls, delayed marriage for young men, breakdown of social capital spending, and increased prevalence of consanguineous marriage. I follow the models with a discussion of the shortcomings of the literature to date, such as failure to account for human - especially women's - agency; concerns about representation of research subjects; environmental determinism; and overrepresentation of theory at lower levels of analysis. I conclude with calls for more research in this nascent area of study via comparative case studies and regression analysis.
