AB  - This study employs a meta-analysis methodology to examine the impacts of human capital and farmers' risk preferences on their decisions regarding sustainable farming practices. By analyzing 143 peer-reviewed studies, we provide valuable insights for policymakers and environmental activists aiming to promote sustainable agriculture worldwide. Our findings confirm that education, experience and agricultural extension in form of human capital play the significant role in fostering the adoption of sustainable farming practices. Moreover, we find that farmers' attitudes toward risk significantly influence their decision-making, as higher risk aversion reduces their willingness to adopt sustainable practices, inversely, risk loving stimulates their sustainable practices adoption.
